Introduction to Set in Java

Set is an interface in Java used to store a collection of unique elements.

👉 Main idea:

no duplicates allowed
порядок обычно не гарантируется (зависит от реализации)
Key Features of Set
does NOT allow duplicates
can contain null (зависит от реализации)
not index-based (нет get(index))
part of the Collection Framework
Common Set Implementations
HashSet → most used, no order
LinkedHashSet → maintains insertion order
TreeSet → sorted elements
HashSet in Java

HashSet is the most commonly used implementation of Set.

👉 It is based on hashing (internally uses a HashMap).

How HashSet works (simple idea)
when you add an element → Java calculates its hashCode()
uses equals() to check duplicates
if element already exists → it will NOT be added
Creating a HashSet
import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();
Adding Elements
set.add("Apple");
set.add("Banana");
set.add("Apple"); // duplicate → ignored
Removing Elements
set.remove("Banana");
Checking Elements
set.contains("Apple");
Iterating over HashSet
for (String item : set) {
    System.out.println(item);
}
Important Features of HashSet
no duplicates
no guaranteed order
allows one null value
not thread-safe
fast operations
Performance
Operation	Complexity
add()	O(1)
remove()	O(1)
contains()	O(1)
HashSet vs List
Feature	HashSet	List
Duplicates	❌	✅
Order	❌	✅
Index access	❌	✅
When to use HashSet

Use it when:

you need unique elements
fast lookup is important
order does NOT matter
Summary
Set stores unique elements
HashSet uses hashing
very fast: O(1)
ignores duplicates
most commonly used Set implementation
